    en: "Sometimes an employer makes working conditions so intolerable that the employee has no choice but to quit. Under the law, this is called constructive discharge — and it is treated the same as being fired. If the employer deliberately created or allowed conditions that no reasonable person would tolerate — severe harassment, dangerous conditions, drastic pay cuts, humiliation — the employee may have claims for wrongful termination, unemployment insurance, and damages even though they technically resigned."
